subSubSection.paragraph:
Topsent (1904)
reported 

Gellius flagellifer

from the Azores (
845–1360 m
). Oxea size ranges were from 335–345 × 8–10 μm in the more shallow station, to 620–680 × 18–20 μm at the deeper stations, suggesting a relationship between oxea size and depth. In the Azores material flagellosigmas reached sizes of up to 118 μm, and normal sigmas occurred in a large size range of 30–80 μm, suggesting the presence of size categories in both. It is possible that the Azores specimens conform to the Irish material, at least the shallower sample (but there is some doubt over the identity of the deeper sample, see below).
